<section id="morphology">
  <h2>3. Morphology</h2>
  <p>This chapter describes the internal structure of words in Tadaksahak. It includes verb morphology, noun morphology, pronouns, adjectives, and other word classes.</p>
  <h3>3.1 Verbs</h3>
  <p>The verbal system distinguishes between perfective and imperfective aspects, and includes causative and passive derivations...</p>
  <ul>
    <li>3.1.1 Person Marking</li>
    <li>3.1.2 Tense/Aspect Markers</li>
    <li>3.1.3 Negation</li>
    <li>3.1.4 Derivational Processes</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>3.2 Nouns</h3>
  <p>Nouns in Tadaksahak show number and gender distinctions. Pluralization is marked by suffixes or tonal changes.</p>
  <h3>3.3 Pronouns and Determiners</h3>
  <p>The language uses independent, subject and object pronouns with person/number distinction.</p>
  <h3>3.4 Adjectives and Adverbs</h3>
  <p>Most adjectives are of nominal origin and agree in number with their head nouns.</p>
  <h3>3.5 Postpositions</h3>
  <p>Postpositions are used instead of prepositions. They follow the noun phrase and show some agreement markers.</p>
</section>
<!-- üìò Chapitre 4 : Syntax -->
<section id="syntax">
  <h2>4. Syntax</h2>
  <p>This chapter describes the syntactic structures of Tadaksahak, focusing on noun phrases, word order, subordination, relativization, and information structure.</p>

  <h3>4.1 Noun Phrases</h3>
  <p>Noun phrases may include determiners, possessors, adjectives, and numerals. They follow a consistent order: Noun ‚Äì Adjective ‚Äì Numeral ‚Äì Possessor ‚Äì Demonstrative.</p>
  
  <h3>4.2 Use of MAN Morphemes</h3>
  <p>The language has a special morpheme MAN, used in relativization, topicalization, and sometimes as a focus particle. It precedes the verb and carries syntactic weight.</p>

  <h3>4.3 Argument Structure</h3>
  <p>Basic word order is Subject‚ÄìVerb‚ÄìObject. Indirect objects precede direct ones in ditransitive constructions. Arguments are often marked by tone and particle.</p>

  <h3>4.4 Copular Clauses</h3>
  <p>Copular clauses are of two types: equative and locative. The copula may be overt or null depending on tense and emphasis.</p>

  <h3>4.5 Relative Clauses</h3>
  <p>Relative clauses follow the noun they modify and are introduced by the MAN morpheme. They maintain verb-final order internally.</p>

  <h3>4.6 Negation Particles</h3>
  <p>Negation is marked by a negative particle preceding the verb. The particle may vary slightly depending on aspect.</p>

  <h3>4.7 Information Structure</h3>
  <p>Focus is marked syntactically and sometimes prosodically. Sentence-initial placement and MAN marking are common focus strategies.</p>

  <h3>4.8 Complex Sentences</h3>
  <p>Complex sentences use subordination, coordination, and serial verb constructions. Subordinators like ‚Äòbecause‚Äô, ‚Äòwhen‚Äô, and ‚Äòif‚Äô exist and precede the embedded clause.</p>
</section>
